[There is much logic involved in the discussion above, and I for one am in full agreement that superspreaders have played a major role in the transmission of this virus. Both the SARS-CoV-1 (2002-2003) and the MERS-CoV (ongoing in the Arabian Peninsula since 2012), both cousins of the SARS-CoV-2, have been involved with superspreading events. Perhaps the "true" R0 has not been as high as many forecasters have cited, but rather the impact of the superspreading events in locations where intense contact tracing was not done, gave a misleading impression/calculation on the transmissibility of this virus. This discussion is all the more important as a justification for as complete contact tracing as possible, to avoid repetitive superspreading events, especially when the viral load is at maximal levels in an infected individual beginning prior to the onset of symptoms. A piece of information missing in the discussion above of the choir practice is whether the superspreader was in fact asymptomatic at the time of the choir practice.- Mod.MPP

HealthMap/ProMED map of Washington State, United States: https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=7473860,4652]

